------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Even out of the supporters of the Entrepreneurs' Party 
which, 
through its only member in the parliament is more often than not 
opposed to the government, 65 percent approve the performance of 
both the government and the president. For supporters of the 
central and coalition factions the 'polarity' is in place, of 
course, with 75 and 63 percent respectively not satisfied with 
the government's performance. 
  The clearest positions on powers-that-be are taken by those 
respondents who support the Democratic Labor Party and the 
League of Pensioners--62 percent of the first, and 53 percent of 
the second support neither the government nor the president (all 
these examples are based on opinions held by Estonian citizens). 
  As usual, we also asked a separate question to establish the 
most trusted institution of power. "Please compare the 
performance of the parliament, with that of the president and 
the opposition, and say whose performance you trust most?" 
was the question. Responses to this question also show the 
president taking the lead. 
  Responses broke down as follows: 


